{"id":"2303.09943","submitter":"Antoine Goldsborough","authors":"Antoine Goldsborough and Alessandro Sisto","title":"Random divergence of groups","comments":"21 pages. 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The divergence of a group is a quasi-isometry invariant defined in terms of\npairs of points and lengths of paths avoiding a suitable ball around the\nidentity. In this paper we study \"random divergence'', meaning the divergence\nat two points chosen according to independent random walks or Markov chains;\nthe Markov chains version can be turned into a quasi-isometry invariant. We\nshow that in many cases, such as for relatively hyperbolic groups, mapping\nclass groups, and right-angled Artin groups, the divergence at two randomly\nchosen points is with high probability equivalent to the divergence of the\ngroup. That is, generic points realise the largest possible divergence.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Mar 2023 13:01:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-20"}
